      {
         "id": "SECTION_soropan",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Between the two\n\nIn general terms, we can understand that both the Soroban and the Suanpan (算盤) have characteristics of both number systems we have studied so far.\n\n#### In common with indigenous systems\n\nWhen representing a number on any version of the abacus, we always move the markers toward the bar. When no marker has been moved, we have the value 0, and we accumulate values up to the limit of 9 (<htcite0>).\n\n#### In common with the Indo-Arabic system\n\nSince each column of the abacuses represents only one number in the range of 0 to 9, to deal with higher orders it is necessary to use the other columns to represent the other orders, as we will see in the following.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "339c7ff5-8365-49bb-a1cd-ad5a13d5fd86",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
